-- Japan, Taiwan, Thailand, India, Malaysia: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   K h a l i d   Q a y u m
-- 2011-02-07T22:38:44Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-07/japan-taiwan-thailand-india-malaysia-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Finance Minister  Yoshihiko Noda , Economy Minister  Kaoru Yosano  and Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold
media briefings.  The  Finance Ministry  will auction 40-year  government bonds 
and report the nation’s balance of payment statistics for
December. The Bank of Japan will report the nation’s money stock
for January.  The Cabinet Office will release the Economy-Watchers report
for January.  The yield on the 1.2 percent government bond due December
2020 was 1.295 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker. The yen traded at
82.33 per dollar at 7:28 a.m. in Tokyo.    India : The central bank will sell 50 billion rupees ($1.1
billion) of 91-day treasury bills and 30 billion rupees of 364-
day treasury bills tomorrow.  The yield on the benchmark 7.8 percent bond due May 2020
was 8.22 percent. The rupee was at 45.5375 per dollar.  Malaysia: The central bank will sell a combined 3 billion
ringgit ($988 million) of 126-day and 364-day notes tomorrow. It
also plans to sell 400 million ringgit of one-year Islamic bonds
and 1.5 billion ringgit of 61-day Islamic notes tomorrow.  The yield on the 3.835 percent bond due August 2015 was
3.40 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0375.  Taiwan: The central bank will release foreign-exchange
reserves data for January. Reserves stood at $382 billion at the
end of December.  The yield on the 1 percent note due January 2016 was 1.057
percent as of Jan. 28, the last day it traded. Financial markets
were closed last week for the Lunar New Year holidays. The  Taiwan dollar  was at NT$29.20 against the dollar.  Thailand: The Bank of Thailand will sell a combined 62
billion baht ($2 billion) of 28-, 91- and 182-day bills.  The baht was at 30.72.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Khalid Qayum in Singapore at 
